Bisti Badlands with @chrissheridanvisuals  on top of the mountain communicating with the aliens.  The Bisti Badlands are a wonderful place to photograph the night sky. Very little light pollution and crystal clear skies.  Taken with a Canon 5D IV, 14mm Sigma Art f1.4 at f2.0, 11 frames stitched in photoshop, at ISO 10,000 and 20 seconds.

A MILKY WAY VIEW FROM MARS ‚Ä¢
We've all had those experiences when another photographer accidentally throws light onto the foreground while we are exposing for a Milky Way shot. After being out for quite a few hours in the Bisti Wilderness on a cold night in May, I couldn't resist the "one last comp" before heading out for a twilight drive back to the hotel in Farmington, NM. I didn't verbally express that I was exposing, and my friend, @jeff_vanuga fired up his pick up truck, the vehicle throwing a plethora of light onto the foreground. Rather than becoming frustrated, I was immediately inspired by the look, and for a moment I felt like I was shooting astrophotography from the surface of the red planet, Mars. In hopes of creating more inspiring accidental moments, I continued shooting as Jeff moved the truck around. ‚Ä¢
The take away here is that some things in life will be out of our control at times - it's how you react and how you choose to perceive those moments that can dictate the final outcome of the situation, otherwise known as a paradigm shift. Inspire yourself to be inspired. ‚Ä¢
I'm sharing a couple of the unedited original exposures (swipe left) so that you can see the inspiration behind the creation of this shot. Although this is a single astrophotography shot, I've added a couple elements for effect in order to better convey my story - the Rover (licensed from Adobe Stock); the dust cloud on the horizon; lastly, I enhanced a star in the sky to resemble what Earth might look like in the distance. Indeed, Rover misses his home. ‚Ä¢
